{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39d77cb4-acce-44f0-91ad-ab02d9d371a3","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** – downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** – re-installs the *already-resolved* versions of your workloads (fixes corrupted installations but doesn't fetch newer packages).\n\nSince the SDK moved forward and your workload packages are now behind, `update` will pull the matching MAUI packs for the new SDK. After updating, do a clean build:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet clean\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf it still fails, check `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-*`) is present.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3e01bbf2-d60c-4ee1-8afb-bed08820f857","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to look anything up.","outputTokens":256,"requestId":"E83B:21DC3D:256785E:296BBAA:69F93E27"},"id":"8c3679ca-552c-444e-a502-67a41293663c","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:47:42.787Z","parentId":"4f4b8d26-be95-4e71-88b0-cb4db27f51c1"}
